## The Specific Open Calculation

The 5:1 ratio requires one remaining calculation:

**Compute the running of g(μ) from the DST Planck-scale value g(m_Pl) = α_G to the seesaw scale g(M_N).**

The DST prediction: g(M_N) = α_W. This means the cross-coupling between the radial displacement (dark matter) and the rotational displacement (visible matter) runs from the gravitational coupling at the Planck scale to the weak coupling at the seesaw scale. 

This is not surprising in the DST framework: at the seesaw scale (which equals the SU(2) condensation scale), the SU(2) force becomes relevant, and the coupling between φ_r and the Φ_θ condensate is set by the SU(2) coupling constant at that scale. The DST displacement fields are mediated by the same coupling as the weak force at the condensation scale where the weak sector forms.

# 5. The Complete Picture

**What happens at each scale:**

| **Scale** | **DST event** | **Consequence** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| m_Pl ≈ 10¹⁹ GeV | EM condensate forms, g = α_G | m_DM = m_e |
| m_GUT ≈ 10¹⁶ GeV | SU(5) symmetry breaks | SU(3) + SU(2) + U(1) separate |
| M_N ≈ 10⁹ GeV | N decays, g = α_W | η_b and Y_DM both produced |
| Λ_QCD ≈ 200 MeV | SU(3) confinement | Protons form from quarks |
| T ≈ m_e | e⁺e⁻ annihilation | η_b locked in, Y_DM → Ω_DM/Ω_b |

The ratio 5.4 is produced by the relationship between g(m_Pl) = α_G (which gives m_DM = m_e) and g(M_N) = α_W (which determines the dark matter production rate relative to baryons). The universe's dark-to-visible matter ratio is the DST cross-coupling RG flow, compressed into one number.

**Ω_DM/Ω_b = 5.363 ≈ g²_cog(M_N) × m_p / (m_e × ε_CP)**

*= α_W × m_p / (m_e × ε_CP_DST)*

*= (weak coupling) × (proton/electron mass) / (CP asymmetry)*

Three coupling constants, two mass scales, one ratio. All determined by the DST geometry. The specific value 5.4 requires computing the running of g from α_G to α_W — a tractable calculation that will either confirm or test this framework.

